Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER STRUCTURE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer state for the Erlang frontend. Erlang's lexical structure is
distinct: atoms are lowercase-leading identifiers, Variables are
uppercase-leading, '-' followed by a lowercase letter at file scope is
a module attribute (-module/-export/...). Binary syntax uses <<...>>
delimiters. The lexer maintains line/column for diagnostics; lexemes
and lines slots are reserved for an interned-text cache and line-start
index that downstream parsers may opportunistically populate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 actively-used fields followed by 3 reserved). Live
fields per create_erlang_lexer: source (0), position (8), len (16),
current_line (24), current_column (32). The tokens (40), lexemes
(48), and lines (56) slots described in the type are not written by
create; populating them is the caller's responsibility for cached
lexers.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangLexer":
    source as Integer
    position as Integer
    len as Integer
    current_line as Integer
    current_column as Integer
    tokens as Integer
    lexemes as Integer
    lines as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN LEXER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates and primes the lexer record. The source byte length is
cached once so the hot peek/advance path can rely on it without
re-measuring. line and column start at 1 to match editor-1-based
diagnostics; position starts at 0 (byte index).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source length via StringCore.string_length. Layout.allocate(40)
returns the lexer handle. Writes source (offset 0), position 0
(offset 8), source_len (offset 16), line 1 (offset 24), column 1
(offset 32). The trailing 8 bytes of the 40-byte record reserved for
tokens/lexemes/lines remain zero (caller-initialised on demand).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_erlang_lexer" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create and initialize Erlang lexer

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize lexer state with source code and position tracking.
    Erlang uses atoms (lowercase), Variables (uppercase), and unique operators.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source_code
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Main scanner. Erlang dispatch is unusual because case discrimination
carries semantic weight: '-' followed by a lowercase letter must be
recognised as the start of a module attribute (the parser cannot
recover the distinction later because '-' before lowercase is also a
valid unary-minus on an atom expression in some positions). Similarly
'?' followed by uppercase starts a macro reference. '<<' / '>>'
binary delimiters need two-byte lookahead before they can be
disambiguated from '<'/'>' comparisons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips whitespace/comments. EOF check via position vs len. Reads first
byte via string_char_at. Branch by first byte:
  '-' (45) with next byte is_lowercase_letter -> lex_module_attribute
  is_lowercase_letter -> lex_atom
  39 ('\'') -> lex_quoted_atom
  is_uppercase_letter or '_' (95) -> lex_variable
  '?' (63) with next is_uppercase_letter -> lex_macro_variable
  is_digit -> lex_number
  '"' (34) -> lex_string
  '$' (36) -> lex_char (character literal $a, $\n)
  '<' (60) with next '<' -> TOKEN_LBIN (binary open)
  '>' (62) with next '>' -> TOKEN_RBIN (binary close)
Any other byte -> lex_operator_or_punct.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source; every dispatch path consumes at least one byte
(either via the specialist proc or directly through advance_position)
so the lexer cannot spin on malformed input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from Erlang source

    @Reasoning:
    Erlang lexer handles atoms (lowercase), Variables (uppercase),
    module attributes (-module), operators (!, ?, ::), and binary syntax <<>>.
    @End Reasoning

    proc skip_whitespace_and_comments from lexer

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    If pos is greater than or equal to len:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, pos, pos
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

    Note: Check for module attributes (starts with -)
    If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
        If pos plus 1 is less than len:
            Let next_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
            If proc is_lowercase_letter with next_ch is equal to 1:
                Return proc lex_module_attribute from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for atoms (lowercase or quoted)
    If proc is_lowercase_letter with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_atom from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for quoted atoms
    If ch is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Return proc lex_quoted_atom from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for Variables (uppercase or underscore)
    If proc is_uppercase_letter with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_variable from lexer
    End If

    If ch is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Return proc lex_variable from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for macro variables (?NAME)
    If ch is equal to 63:  Note: ?
        If pos plus 1 is less than len:
            Set next_ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
            If proc is_uppercase_letter with next_ch is equal to 1:
                Return proc lex_macro_variable from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for numbers
    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for strings
    If ch is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc lex_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for character literals
    If ch is equal to 36:  Note: $
        Return proc lex_char from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for binary syntax <<
    If ch is equal to 60:  Note: <
        If pos plus 1 is less than len:
            Set next_ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
            If next_ch is equal to 60:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos plus 2
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBIN, pos, pos plus 2
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for binary syntax >>
    If ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
        If pos plus 1 is less than len:
            Set next_ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
            If next_ch is equal to 62:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos plus 2
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBIN, pos, pos plus 2
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for operators and punctuation
    Return proc lex_operator_or_punct from lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WHITESPACE AND COMMENT HANDLING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Loops between whitespace and comment skipping so any interleaving of
the two is fully consumed in a single call. Erlang comments are %-to-
end-of-line only (no block comments per the spec) so the inner state
machine is trivial.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer infinite while. Each iteration: skip_whitespace consumes any
run of whitespace; try_skip_comment consumes a single % comment and
returns 0 if no comment was present. When try_skip_comment returns 0
the outer loop terminates (returning 1).
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace_and_comments" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace from lexer

        Let skipped_comment be proc try_skip_comment from lexer
        If skipped_comment is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes the run of whitespace bytes at the cursor with separate
handling for LF (which must advance the line counter via
advance_newline) versus the other whitespace forms (space/tab/CR
which only advance the column).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops while pos < len. Reads current byte; 32 (space), 9 (tab),
or 13 (CR) call advance_position; 10 (LF) calls advance_newline.
Any other byte returns 1 immediately, leaving the cursor at the
first non-whitespace byte. The shadow pos variable is kept in sync
with the lexer's own offset so the loop condition can be re-checked
without an extra memory_get.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            proc advance_position from lexer
            Set pos to pos plus 1

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                proc advance_position from lexer
                Set pos to pos plus 1

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                    proc advance_newline from lexer
                    Set pos to pos plus 1

                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 13:  Note: Carriage return
                        proc advance_position from lexer
                        Set pos to pos plus 1

                    Otherwise:
                        Return 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a % line comment if one is present at the cursor. Returns 1
on success so the caller (skip_whitespace_and_comments) can loop;
returns 0 if no comment was found so the caller can stop looping.
The terminating LF is left in the buffer so skip_whitespace will pick
it up and bump the line counter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
EOF guard returns 0. Reads current byte; if not '%' (37) returns 0.
Otherwise advances past '%', then loops consuming bytes via
advance_position until LF (10) is encountered or pos reaches len.
LF is NOT consumed - it is left for skip_whitespace. Returns 1
either way once a comment has been entered.
@End Implementation
Process called "try_skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Try to skip Erlang comment (% to end of line)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    If pos is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

    Note: Check for % comment
    If ch is equal to 37:  Note: %
        proc advance_position from lexer
        Set pos to pos plus 1

        While pos is less than len:
            Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
            If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                Return 1
            End If
            proc advance_position from lexer
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End While

        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATOM AND VARIABLE LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an unquoted Erlang atom: a lowercase-leading identifier whose
tail may include letters, digits, underscore, and @ (per the Erlang
spec). After scanning, the lexeme is checked against the keyword set
via match_erlang_keyword; on match the token is emitted with the
keyword's TOKEN_* code rather than TOKEN_ATOM so the parser doesn't
need to re-classify reserved words.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos = position. While loop consumes is_atom_char
bytes (case-insensitive letter, digit, '_', or '@'). Note: the
internal break-via-if-then-if pattern is the bootstrap's stand-in
for an explicit break statement; control falls through naturally when
is_atom_char returns 0 because pos still increments at the end of the
loop body. After the loop, position is updated and match_erlang_keyword
is consulted; non-zero result yields a keyword token, otherwise
TOKEN_ATOM.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_atom" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex unquoted atom (starts with lowercase)

    @Reasoning:
    Erlang atoms start with lowercase letter or are quoted with '.
    Valid characters: letters, digits, underscore, @
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
        Let is_atom_char be proc is_atom_char from ch

        If is_atom_char is equal to 0:
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: End of atom
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos

    Note: Check if this is a keyword
    Let keyword_type be proc match_erlang_keyword with source, start_pos, pos
    If keyword_type is not equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with keyword_type, start_pos, pos
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ATOM, start_pos, pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an apostrophe-delimited atom 'foo bar' (allows spaces, mixed
case, and non-identifier characters in the atom name). Backslash
escapes are consumed without interpretation; a literal LF inside the
atom advances the line counter. Unterminated atoms produce
TOKEN_LEX_ERROR so the parser can report a diagnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts at start_pos + 1 (skip the opening apostrophe). Loops while
pos < len: closing apostrophe (39) emits TOKEN_ATOM with the full
span (including delimiters). Backslash (92) advances pos by 2 to
skip the escape payload. LF (10) calls advance_newline. Any other
byte advances pos by 1. Falling off the end (no closing apostrophe)
emits TOKEN_LEX_ERROR.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source; EOF-aware termination prevents unbounded scan on
unterminated atoms.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "lex_quoted_atom" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex quoted atom 'atom name'

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip opening '

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 39:  Note: '
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ATOM, start_pos, pos
        End If

        If ch is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set pos to pos plus 2  Note: Skip escape sequence

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                proc advance_newline from lexer
                Set pos to pos plus 1

            Otherwise:
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Unterminated atom
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEX_ERROR, start_pos, pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an Erlang Variable (capital-leading or underscore-leading).
The tail accepts the same is_atom_char set as unquoted atoms because
the syntactic distinction between atoms and Variables is determined
solely by the first character. '_' alone is a "don't care" anonymous
variable; '_Foo' is a meaningful-named anonymous binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos. Consumes a run of is_atom_char bytes via the
same fall-through-by-incrementing-pos idiom used in lex_atom. After
the loop, updates the lexer position and emits TOKEN_VARIABLE; no
keyword check is needed because no Erlang keyword starts with an
uppercase letter or underscore.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_variable" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex variable (starts with uppercase or underscore)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
        Let is_var_char be proc is_atom_char from ch

        If is_var_char is equal to 0:
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: End of variable
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_VARIABLE, start_pos, pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a preprocessor macro reference ?NAME or ?MODULE. Caller has
verified the leading '?' and that what follows is uppercase. The
resulting token preserves the leading '?' as part of the lexeme
because the parser needs to recognise the macro context (the
expansion happens in a separate preprocessor pass).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts at start_pos + 1 (consumes '?'). Consumes a run of
is_atom_char bytes for the macro name. Updates lexer position and
emits TOKEN_MACRO_VAR with the full span (including the '?').
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_macro_variable" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex macro variable ?NAME

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip ?

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
        Let is_var_char be proc is_atom_char from ch

        If is_var_char is equal to 0:
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: End of macro variable
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MACRO_VAR, start_pos, pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a module attribute declaration such as -module, -export,
-record. The dispatcher in next_token has verified the cursor is on
'-' followed by a lowercase letter so this routine consumes the '-'
and then the attribute name. The lexeme is matched against the known
attribute set via match_module_attribute; on miss the routine rewinds
to emit just the '-' as TOKEN_MINUS so the parser can recover and
treat the trailing identifier as an ordinary atom.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts at start_pos + 1 (consumes '-'). Consumes a run of
is_atom_char bytes for the attribute name. Updates position. Calls
match_module_attribute on the span [start_pos+1, pos); non-zero
result emits the attribute-specific token (including the leading
'-' in the span). On miss, rewinds position to start_pos+1 and emits
a single-byte TOKEN_MINUS, leaving the identifier portion to be
re-lexed on the next call.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_module_attribute" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex module attribute (-module, -export, etc.)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip -

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
        Let is_atom_char be proc is_atom_char from ch

        If is_atom_char is equal to 0:
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: End of attribute
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos

    Note: Check if this is a known attribute
    Let attr_type be proc match_module_attribute with source, start_pos plus 1, pos
    If attr_type is not equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with attr_type, start_pos, pos
    End If

    Note: Return as - operator if not recognized
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, start_pos plus 1
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS, start_pos, start_pos plus 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KEYWORD AND ATTRIBUTE MATCHING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Classifies a scanned atom lexeme against Erlang's reserved-word set.
Returns the matched TOKEN_* code, or 0 to indicate "not a keyword,
emit as TOKEN_ATOM". The keyword set covers control-flow words
(after/begin/case/catch/cond/end/fun/if/let/of/receive/try/when),
boolean/logical operators (and/andalso/or/orelse/xor/not), bitwise
operators (band/bnot/bor/bsl/bsr/bxor), and integer arithmetic
(div/rem).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes the substring spanning [start, end_pos) and compares it
against each keyword via StringCore.string_equals. Each match returns
the corresponding TOKEN_* constant immediately. Falls through to 0.
The substring allocation is intentional - downstream code may keep
the lexeme around for error reporting; the StringCore handle's
lifetime aligns with the lexer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear scan over ~25 keywords. Performance-critical callers can
substitute a perfect hash or trie if profiling shows this hot;
current Erlang corpora are small enough that the linear cascade is
acceptable.
@End Performance_Hints
