Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMBER LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an Erlang numeric literal. Erlang's numeric grammar is
unusually rich: decimal integers and floats are standard, but
base-prefixed integers use the 'BASE#DIGITS' form (e.g. 16#FF for
255, 2#1010 for 10, 8#777 for 511). Floats may carry e/E exponents
with optional sign. The is_float flag distinguishes the two output
token types.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos. Consumes the leading digit run. If the next
byte is '#' (35), the digits read so far are parsed as the base
integer (StringCore.string_to_integer); the base prefix is consumed
and a second digit loop accepts is_digit when base <= 10 or
is_hex_digit otherwise. The base-prefixed result is emitted as
TOKEN_INTEGER unconditionally. Without a '#', a '.' (46) followed by
fractional digits sets is_float and consumes the fraction. An 'e'
(101) or 'E' (69) exponent marker sets is_float, optionally consumes
a +/- sign, and consumes the exponent digit run. Final token is
TOKEN_FLOAT or TOKEN_INTEGER based on the is_float flag.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex numeric literal (integer or float, with optional base)

    @Reasoning:
    Erlang supports: 123, 1.23, 16#FF (hex), 2#1010 (binary), 8#77 (octal)
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos

    Let is_float be 0
    Let base be 10

    Note: Lex integer part
    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
        Let is_digit_val be proc is_digit from ch

        If is_digit_val is equal to 1:
            Set pos to pos plus 1

        Otherwise:
            If 1 is equal to 1:
                Note: Break
                If 1 is not equal to 1:
                    Note: Force break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check for base notation (e.g., 16#FF)
    If pos is less than len:
        Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 35:  Note: #
            Note: Extract base
            Let base_len be pos minus start_pos
            Let base_str be proc substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, base_len
            Set base to proc string_to_integer from StringCore with base_str

            Set pos to pos plus 1

            Note: Lex digits in specified base
            While pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                Let is_valid be 0

                If base is less than or equal to 10:
                    Set is_valid to proc is_digit from ch

                Otherwise:
                    Set is_valid to proc is_hex_digit from ch
                End If

                If is_valid is equal to 1:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1

                Otherwise:
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Break
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER, start_pos, pos
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for decimal point (float)
    If pos is less than len:
        Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 46:  Note: .
            Set is_float to 1
            Set pos to pos plus 1

            Note: Lex fractional part
            While pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                Set is_digit_val to proc is_digit from ch

                If is_digit_val is equal to 1:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1

                Otherwise:
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Break
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent (e or E)
    If pos is less than len:
        Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 101:  Note: e
            Set is_float to 1
            Set pos to pos plus 1

            If pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                If ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                End If
                If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                End If
            End If

            While pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                Set is_digit_val to proc is_digit from ch

                If is_digit_val is equal to 1:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1

                Otherwise:
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Break
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If

        If ch is equal to 69:  Note: E
            Set is_float to 1
            Set pos to pos plus 1

            If pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                If ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                End If
                If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                End If
            End If

            While pos is less than len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
                Set is_digit_val to proc is_digit from ch

                If is_digit_val is equal to 1:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1

                Otherwise:
                    If 1 is equal to 1:
                        Note: Break
                        If 1 is not equal to 1:
                            Note: Force break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos

    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_FLOAT, start_pos, pos
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER, start_pos, pos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING AND CHARACTER LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a "..." string literal. In Erlang strings are syntactic sugar
for lists of integer codepoints, but the lexer still emits a single
TOKEN_STRING containing the raw lexeme; expansion happens in the AST
construction phase. Backslash escapes are consumed without
interpretation; embedded LFs advance the line counter via
advance_newline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts at start_pos + 1 (skips opening '"'). Loops:
  '"' (34) consumes and emits TOKEN_STRING with the full span.
  Backslash (92) advances pos by 2 (skip escape payload).
  LF (10) calls advance_newline.
  Anything else advances by 1.
Falling off the end emits TOKEN_LEX_ERROR for unterminated strings.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source; EOF-aware termination prevents unbounded scan.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal (list of integers in Erlang)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip opening "

    While pos is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        If ch is equal to 34:  Note: "
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, start_pos, pos
        End If

        If ch is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set pos to pos plus 2  Note: Skip escape sequence

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                proc advance_newline from lexer
                Set pos to pos plus 1

            Otherwise:
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Unterminated string
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEX_ERROR, start_pos, pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an Erlang character literal '$' followed by one character or
escape sequence (e.g. $a, $\n, $\t). The value of such a literal is
the integer codepoint of the character; the lexer emits TOKEN_CHAR
with the full lexeme so the AST construction can decode the escape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts at start_pos + 1 (skips '$'). EOF guard emits TOKEN_LEX_ERROR.
Reads the character: backslash (92) consumes 2 bytes (escape payload);
otherwise consumes 1 byte. Position is updated and TOKEN_CHAR emitted
with the full [$X] or [$\X] span.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex character literal ($a, $\n, etc.)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip $

    If pos is greater than or equal to len:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEX_ERROR, start_pos, pos
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

    Note: Handle escape sequences
    If ch is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash
        Set pos to pos plus 2  Note: Skip escape sequence

    Otherwise:
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CHAR, start_pos, pos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPERATOR AND PUNCTUATION LEXING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Fallback dispatcher for non-alphanumeric bytes. Recognises Erlang's
operator and punctuation tokens with the necessary lookahead.
Multi-byte operators include: '->' (arrow, function head), '=>' (map
field), '==' (equal), '=/=' (not equal), '=:=' (exact equal), '=<'
(less-or-equal - note Erlang reverses the conventional '<=' spelling),
'++' (list concat), '--' (list subtract), '::' (type spec), ':='
(map update), '>=' (greater-or-equal), '..' (range), '...' (ellipsis).
Single-byte tokens cover send ('!'), match ('='), pipe ('|'), all
arithmetic, both bracket families, comma/semicolon/colon/dot/hash/
question/at.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the first byte unconditionally to advance the cursor. If a
second byte is available, attempts to match each multi-byte sequence
by inspecting (ch, next_ch) and optionally a third byte for the
three-char '=/=' / '=:=' / '...'. On match emits the dedicated
TOKEN_* and returns. Otherwise the cursor remains one byte past
start_pos and the routine drops into a long if-else cascade that
maps the single byte to its TOKEN_* (TOKEN_SEND for '!',
TOKEN_MATCH for '=', etc.). Unrecognised bytes emit TOKEN_LEX_ERROR.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_operator_or_punct" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex operators and punctuation

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let pos be start_pos

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
    Set pos to pos plus 1

    Note: Multi-character operators
    If pos is less than len:
        Let next_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

        Note: Arrow ->
        If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
            If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ARROW, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        Note: Double arrow =>
        If ch is equal to 61:  Note: =
            If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW, start_pos, pos
            End If

            If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: ==
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUAL, start_pos, pos
            End If

            If next_ch is equal to 47:  Note: =/=
                If pos plus 1 is less than len:
                    Let third_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
                    If third_ch is equal to 61:
                        Set pos to pos plus 2
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, start_pos, pos
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            If next_ch is equal to 58:  Note: =:=
                If pos plus 1 is less than len:
                    Set third_ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
                    If third_ch is equal to 61:
                        Set pos to pos plus 2
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EXACT_EQUAL, start_pos, pos
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            If next_ch is equal to 60:  Note: =<
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        Note: List operators
        If ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
            If next_ch is equal to 43:  Note: ++
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS_PLUS, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
            If next_ch is equal to 45:  Note: --
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_SUBTRACT, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        Note: Colon operators
        If ch is equal to 58:  Note: :
            If next_ch is equal to 58:  Note: ::
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON_COLON, start_pos, pos
            End If

            If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: :=
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLONEQUAL, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        Note: Greater/less operators
        If ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
            If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: >=
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If

        Note: Dots
        If ch is equal to 46:  Note: .
            If next_ch is equal to 46:  Note: ..
                If pos plus 1 is less than len:
                    Set third_ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos plus 1
                    If third_ch is equal to 46:  Note: ...
                        Set pos to pos plus 2
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TRIPLE_DOT, start_pos, pos
                    End If
                End If

                Set pos to pos plus 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_DOT, start_pos, pos
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Single-character operators and punctuation
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos

    If ch is equal to 33:  Note: ! (send operator)
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEND, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 61:  Note: = (match operator)
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MATCH, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 124:  Note: | (list cons)
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_CONS, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 43:  Note: +
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 47:  Note: /
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SLASH, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 35:  Note: # (record/map)
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HASH, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 63:  Note: ? (macro or catch)
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_QUESTION, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 64:  Note: @
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AT, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 40:  Note: (
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 41:  Note: )
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 125:  Note: }
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, start_pos, pos
    End If

    If ch is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, start_pos, pos
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEX_ERROR, start_pos, pos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII lowercase classifier. Used by next_token to discriminate between
unquoted atoms (lowercase-leading) and Variables (uppercase-leading)
- the case distinction is semantically significant in Erlang.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range check 97..122 ('a'..'z'); returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_lowercase_letter" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is lowercase letter

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII uppercase classifier. Used by next_token to recognise the
start of an Erlang Variable, and by lex_macro_variable to verify
the byte after '?' is a valid macro-name start.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range check 65..90 ('A'..'Z'); returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_uppercase_letter" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is uppercase letter

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit classifier used by lex_number and the atom-tail scanner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range check 48..57 ('0'..'9'); returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII hex digit classifier used by lex_number's base-prefixed integer
path (when the parsed base is > 10).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_digit; match returns 1. Otherwise range checks 65..70
('A'..'F') and 97..102 ('a'..'f'). Any match returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a hex digit

    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier shared by atoms, Variables, macro
variables, and module attributes. Erlang permits letters (either
case), digits, underscore, and '@' (the latter is conventional in
process-registered atom names) in the tail of these lexemes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Cascade: is_lowercase_letter -> 1; is_uppercase_letter -> 1;
is_digit -> 1; '_' (95) -> 1; '@' (64) -> 1; else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_atom_char" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is valid in atom or variable

    Let is_lower be proc is_lowercase_letter from ch
    If is_lower is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_upper be proc is_uppercase_letter from ch
    If is_upper is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_digit_val be proc is_digit from ch
    If is_digit_val is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 64:  Note: @
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one byte without crossing a line boundary. Bumps both the
byte cursor and the column counter so column tracking remains
accurate for non-newline characters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8) and column (offset 24); writes back pos+1
to offset 8 and col+1 to offset 24. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_position" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position and column

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let col be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, col plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes an LF byte while updating the line counter and resetting
column to 1. Used everywhere the lexer crosses a newline: in
skip_whitespace, inside quoted atoms with embedded LFs, and inside
strings with embedded LFs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8). Writes pos+1 to offset 8, line+1 to offset
16 (NOTE: this routine writes to offset 16 which the type declares
as 'len'; the field naming is misleading - the 16 slot is reused as
current_line counter for the active scan, distinct from the
record's documented layout). Resets column at offset 24 to 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_newline" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position for newline

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 24-byte Token record holding the three fields the parser
needs: token type discriminator and the [start, end_pos) byte span
into the original source. The lexer does not own the source bytes so
this record is small and trivially shareable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Layout.allocate(24). Writes token_type at offset 0, start at offset
8, end_pos at offset 16. Returns the new token handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, start as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token structure

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, start
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, end_pos

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Token output record. Carries only the discriminator and the
source-byte span (start/end_pos as 0-based byte indices into the
source). Lexeme text is reconstructed by the parser via substring
when needed; this keeps tokens uniformly small (24 bytes) and avoids
copying lexeme bytes during lexing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record (3 x i64). Offsets: 0 type (TOKEN_* constant), 8
start_pos, 16 end_pos. Allocated by create_token; freed by the
parser or by the lexer cleanup pass depending on the caller's
ownership protocol.
@End Implementation
Type called "Token":
    type as Integer
    start_pos as Integer
    end_pos as Integer
End Type
